DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());
Context("Numeric");
$na = Compute("6");
$nb = Compute("4");
$nc = Compute("9");
$nd = Compute("2");
$ne = Compute("5");
$nf = Compute("7");
$ng = Compute("10");
$nh = Compute("1");
$ni = Compute("3");
$nj = Compute("8");

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
    Suppose that a binary search tree has the following shape.
$PAR
\{ image("emptytree.png", width=>650, height=>160, tex_size=>700, extra_html_tags=>'alt="sequence of squares"') \} 
$PAR
    Place the integers 1 through 10 on the nodes \(A\) through \(J\) in a manner consistent with
    the definition of a binary search tree. $PAR
\(A:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(B:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(C:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(D:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(E:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(F:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(G:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(H:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(I:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
\(J:\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} $BR
$PAR

Think about how you would describe a general procedure for
    visiting the nodes of a binary search tree in order.

END_TEXT

Context()->normalStrings;
ANS($na->cmp());
ANS($nb->cmp());
ANS($nc->cmp());
ANS($nd->cmp());
ANS($ne->cmp());
ANS($nf->cmp());
ANS($ng->cmp());
ANS($nh->cmp());
ANS($ni->cmp());
ANS($nj->cmp());

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR SOLUTION $PAR
To visit the nodes in order, start at \(H\), and then visit \(D, I, B, E, A, F, J, C, G\).
END_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();

